Using the identity $\sin nx=-\sin (90^\circ-nx)$, substitute $n=1$ into the equation:
\begin{align}
    (\sin x)^7 &= a \sin 7x - b \sin 6x - c \sin 5x - d \sin x \\
    (\sin x)^7 &= a \sin 7x + d \sin x
\end{align}
Since $x$ can be any angle, including $x=0$, $d$ must be equal to $0$. So, the answer is: \boxed{0}.
